Bike Score Data¶

In [62]:
# Create a figure and two subplots
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 6))

# Plot map with 'Bike Score' as color
census_scores.plot(column='Bike Score', cmap='RdYlGn', legend=True, ax=ax1)
ax1.set_title('Map with Bike Score')

# Plot map with 'AQWLE001' as color
census_scores.plot(column='AQWLE001', cmap='RdYlGn', legend=True, ax=ax2)
ax2.set_title('Map with Median Household Income')

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Show the plots
plt.show()
In [60]:
census_scores_clean = census_scores.dropna(subset=['AQWLE001', 'Bike Score'])

# Create scatter plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(census_scores_clean['AQWLE001'], census_scores_clean['Bike Score'], alpha=0.5)
plt.title('Scatter Plot of Median Household Income vs. Bike Score')
plt.xlabel('Median Household Income ($)')
plt.ylabel('Bike Score')
plt.grid(True)

# Show plot
plt.show()
In [61]:
#test for statistical significance

from scipy.stats import pearsonr

# Perform Pearson correlation test
correlation_coefficient, p_value = pearsonr(census_scores_clean['AQWLE001'], census_scores_clean['Bike Score'])

# Print results
print("Pearson correlation coefficient:", correlation_coefficient)
print("p-value:", p_value)

Pearson correlation coefficient: -0.016401624113643078
p-value: 0.6944595989405584

Median household income not statstically significantly associated with bike score¶
